<br>
Looking back through fantasy literature, I've found very little that actually had flowery speech in it.  Rather, roleplay is the suspension of disbelief... actually building a reason for your actions rather than running around and doing things 'just because you can'.<br>
<br>
Good examples might be a wizard who's afraid of snakes (and runs when they get close) or a Warrior who was cheated once by a halfling and now hunts them mercilessly.  Those are just thoughts, but perhaps you get the grist of what I'm saying.  Mode of speech doesn't necessarily determine roleplaying.  Method of action certainly does.  Either way, good luck. <p>Denoi Fishwhiskers<BR>
Taruun of Shar Val<BR><BR>
Master Cook <BR>
Lousy Fletcher<BR>
Grandmaster Lech<BR>
<I>"Show me a good mouser and I'll show you a cat with bad breath" -- Garfield</I></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubjond.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bjond</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 127<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/31/01 10:43:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=995.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Hmm, I can answer some</span><hr size=1> 1. Barbies know human and barbarian.  Elfish is probably the most spoken tongue, but everfrost is a great starting zone and you won't have language issues there.<br>
<br>
2. No bugs for languages, just level-capped and harder to raise.  1 point per hour or per zoning.  So, you can learn 1 point of Elfish, zone, and learn another.  But, you can't learn 1 pt of Elf then 1 pt. of Troll without zoning in between.  I tried to cram a couple of languages at once between zonings and it doesn't work.  Can only do one at a time.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
This means it takes 100 zonings to master each new tongue or roughly 100 minutes depending on zoning and learning speed.  My human monk with 75 INT and very fast zoning mastered in 45-120 minutes, usually about 60 minutes.  Some zones just zone faster and some seem to have an odd bug that slows down /gsay spamming.<br>
<br>
Knowing all languages is huge here.  You will find that most lowbies don't talk much because they expect not to be understood.  If you show you know their tongue, they babble on quite charmingly.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
3. I don't see why not.  All you need is about 50 skilled players to do any zone or mob in the game.  I think there are at least that many on FV, though not in the same guild and not high level yet.<br>
<br>
4. I don't know.  I'm just now starting to be of a level where I can do the lower ones.  I never had any problems with crowds on old servers because we frequented dungeons that the rest of the server thought were too hard to do.  The only spot I haven't pulled is Sleepers -- it wasn't open when I last &quot;quit&quot; EQ (about a year ago).<br>
<br>
At any rate, even the most popular zones here are empty, so wherever you go, crowds are unlikely.  BYOG is mandatory. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#A62A2A>- </font><a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie>Firiona Vie</a><font color=#A62A2A> - </font><a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1>Firiona Vie General Chat</a> <font color=#A62A2A> - </font><a href="http://www.firiona-vie.com/">Firiona Vie</a><font color=#A62A2A> - </font> <center><a href="http://www.firiona-vie.com/fvchat.html" target="_blank"><h3>Chat Room</a></h3></center> <br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 6.5<br>Copyright ©1999-2001 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  